                <p>Soy fabric is made from the fibers of soy bean hulls. Soy requires more water and pesticides than bamboo and hemp, although GMO strains have also been developed. Deforestation to grow more soy is also a concern. Processing includes the use of formaldehyde which is a probable carcinogen (alternatives are being investigated). Unlike during production of bamboo and wood cellulose, the chemicals are reused for soy. Soy beans are also used to make tofu, so manufacturing fabric from it <strong>reduces waste</strong>. Producing this soft, cashmere-like fabric is still <strong>more sustainable than non-organic cotton</strong>, but care is needed to ensure it is grown sustainably.</p>
